00:00:20.660 --> 00:00:23.590
PROFESSOR: Good afternoon.

00:00:23.590 --> 00:00:30.780
So last week, we started
our discussion of atoms.

00:00:30.780 --> 00:00:33.210
So these are, of
course, the key players

00:00:33.210 --> 00:00:35.740
in a course of atomic physics.

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:40.120
And we will reveal the structure
of atoms going from the larger

00:00:40.120 --> 00:00:43.120
energies to the
smaller energies.

00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:46.940
That means we start with
electronic energies mainly

00:00:46.940 --> 00:00:48.960
determined by Coulomb energy.

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:50.820
And then we go to
finer levels which

00:00:50.820 --> 00:00:53.780
are fine structure, hyperfine
structure, Lamb shift, and all

00:00:53.780 --> 00:00:55.300
that.

00:00:55.300 --> 00:01:01.670
So we have started last week
to discuss the Schrodinger

00:01:01.670 --> 00:01:04.970
equation, discuss
hydrogenic energy levels,

00:01:04.970 --> 00:01:11.440
and I pointed out some important
results on typical length

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:14.450
scales and the scaling
of the wave function.

00:01:14.450 --> 00:01:17.060
We will meet that later today.

00:01:17.060 --> 00:01:20.250
But before I continue
with atomic structure,

00:01:20.250 --> 00:01:26.060
I want to start today
to discuss the units.

00:01:26.060 --> 00:01:30.860
The atomic units we are
using to describe the atom.

00:01:30.860 --> 00:01:38.640
So the nat-- and for
every problem in physics,

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:42.240
you have what one may
call natural units.

00:01:44.850 --> 00:01:51.680
And for us these are also
called the atomic units.

00:01:51.680 --> 00:01:53.200
So what are atomic units?

00:01:53.200 --> 00:01:57.850
Well, atomic units are the
units for length, for energy,

00:01:57.850 --> 00:02:00.310
for velocity, for
electric field.

00:02:00.310 --> 00:02:03.850
And all of these
units, you should

00:02:03.850 --> 00:02:07.960
be able to construct them
out of fundamental constants.

00:02:07.960 --> 00:02:11.440
The fundamental constants
which appear in the Schrodinger

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:15.610
equation for the
electron within the atom

00:02:15.610 --> 00:02:22.190
are the charge of the electron,
the mass of the electron,

00:02:22.190 --> 00:02:22.690
and h-bar.

00:02:25.430 --> 00:02:28.760
Now, is there any other
fundamental constant

00:02:28.760 --> 00:02:33.395
we should include here to
construct our natural units?

00:02:37.330 --> 00:02:40.110
c, good question.

00:02:40.110 --> 00:02:42.368
What about c?

00:02:42.368 --> 00:02:44.910
The speed of light.

00:02:44.910 --> 00:02:48.090
Should the speed
of light be part

00:02:48.090 --> 00:02:50.930
of our system of atomic units?

00:03:00.130 --> 00:03:01.060
Let's not go there.

00:03:01.060 --> 00:03:02.520
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:06.150
Because if you set it to
one, you have made a choice.

00:03:06.150 --> 00:03:08.440
You have constrained
your system.

00:03:08.440 --> 00:03:12.030
And you're almost obscuring the
fact whether it should appear

00:03:12.030 --> 00:03:13.330
or not.

00:03:13.330 --> 00:03:15.710
Well, the strong message
I want to give you

00:03:15.710 --> 00:03:19.232
is at the level of
electronic structure,

00:03:19.232 --> 00:03:20.940
at the level of the
Schrodinger equation,

00:03:20.940 --> 00:03:22.600
it should not be there.

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:25.230
Because we are
talking at this point

00:03:25.230 --> 00:03:27.680
about solutions
of the Schrodinger

00:03:27.680 --> 00:03:30.190
equation, the hydrogenic levels.

00:03:30.190 --> 00:03:33.720
And there is no c, no speed
of light in the Schrodinger

00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:34.980
equation.

00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:39.830
So c is not part of the
fundamental constants

00:03:39.830 --> 00:03:42.780
we have to consider now.

00:03:42.780 --> 00:03:45.870
It will later come in the
fine-structure constant,

00:03:45.870 --> 00:03:47.870
but this is a different story.

00:03:47.870 --> 00:03:51.750
So we have three
units, e, m, and c.

00:03:51.750 --> 00:03:55.360
And you can just play
the game of combinatorics

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:59.480
and see can you
find a length which

00:03:59.480 --> 00:04:01.520
consists of those three units.

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:06.030
And, well, it's h
squared, m over e squared.

00:04:06.030 --> 00:04:09.200
This is how you get
the unit of length.

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:13.930
And this length is
called the Bohr radius.

00:04:13.930 --> 00:04:17.860
And indeed, this is
sort of the RMS size

00:04:17.860 --> 00:04:21.165
of the electron in the 1s state.

00:04:21.165 --> 00:04:24.830
You can play the
game again and ask,

00:04:24.830 --> 00:04:29.460
can we construct an energy?

00:04:29.460 --> 00:04:35.050
Well, you find that if
you take e to the four,

00:04:35.050 --> 00:04:39.560
if you take the mass and
finally divide by h square,

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:42.910
then you have a unit of energy.

00:04:42.910 --> 00:04:47.310
And this unit of
energy turns out

00:04:47.310 --> 00:04:55.930
to be one Hartree or 27.2
electron volts or two Rydbergs,

00:04:55.930 --> 00:04:59.690
twice the binding energy of
the electron in the 1s state.

00:04:59.690 --> 00:05:02.900
And we had some discussion last
week that the factor of two

00:05:02.900 --> 00:05:05.600
reflects the virial theorem.

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:08.380
This is actually that one
Hartree is the Coulomb energy

00:05:08.380 --> 00:05:12.340
of the electron in the 1s state,
which is the binding energy.

00:05:12.340 --> 00:05:14.690
But then half of it
is kinetic energy.

00:05:14.690 --> 00:05:18.010
And, therefore, the total
energy of the 1s electron

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:20.950
is half the Coulomb energy.

00:05:20.950 --> 00:05:23.570
And it's that.

00:05:23.570 --> 00:05:25.350
But no.

00:05:25.350 --> 00:05:28.150
OK, so, so far no c.

00:05:28.150 --> 00:05:32.190
The energy, the energy
levels, the wave function.

00:05:32.190 --> 00:05:34.810
If there is no c, no speed
of light in the Schrodinger

00:05:34.810 --> 00:05:38.070
equation, there is no c in the
solution of the Schrodinger

00:05:38.070 --> 00:05:40.540
equation.

00:05:40.540 --> 00:05:43.510
And if you set it 1, sure,
it wouldn't-- I mean,

00:05:43.510 --> 00:05:45.790
if your relativity
equation said c equals 1,

00:05:45.790 --> 00:05:46.740
you obscure the fact.

00:05:46.740 --> 00:05:50.070
But here, it's
definitely not there.

00:05:50.070 --> 00:05:52.485
But now we can also
see, well, there

00:05:52.485 --> 00:05:56.120
are other important energies.

00:05:56.120 --> 00:05:59.350
One energy, and now
I bring in the c

00:05:59.350 --> 00:06:01.570
just because I want to
compare two energies which

00:06:01.570 --> 00:06:05.820
include the speed of light, the
rest energy of the electron.

00:06:05.820 --> 00:06:12.820
Or a very fundamental unit
of length is h-bar over mc.

00:06:12.820 --> 00:06:16.460
Which is the
Compton wavelengths.

00:06:16.460 --> 00:06:19.230
So that's lambda Compton,
the Compton wavelengths

00:06:19.230 --> 00:06:21.540
of the electron.

00:06:21.540 --> 00:06:26.320
And, well, if we
try to figure out

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:30.440
what is the ratio of the
atomic unit of lengths.

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:37.310
And the Compton radius,
we have to multiply

00:06:37.310 --> 00:06:41.420
with a dimensionless unit
which is hc over e squared.

00:06:41.420 --> 00:06:46.430
Or if I take the reverse,
e squared over hc, h-bar c.

00:06:46.430 --> 00:06:52.130
And similarly, here the
dimensionless quantity

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:55.110
to multiply is that.

00:06:55.110 --> 00:07:02.690
So what do we find now here
is we find that what we get

00:07:02.690 --> 00:07:05.944
is a quantity which
I want to call alpha,

00:07:05.944 --> 00:07:07.110
the fine-structure constant.

00:07:09.620 --> 00:07:17.210
And what I find here is the same
constant, alpha to the minus 1,

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:18.795
times the Compton wavelengths.

00:07:24.092 --> 00:07:26.470
Let me discuss the
fine-structure constant

00:07:26.470 --> 00:07:30.750
in a second, but there's
still two more atomic units

00:07:30.750 --> 00:07:32.330
we want to discuss.

00:07:32.330 --> 00:07:36.280
There is the velocity and
there is the electric field.

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:44.290
I can simply get the
velocity by saying, well,

00:07:44.290 --> 00:07:47.720
the velocity enters the
kinetic energy in mv square.

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:51.670
And if I said mv square, I want
to skip all factors of unity.

00:07:51.670 --> 00:07:54.530
So that's not one half,
it's just mv square.

00:07:54.530 --> 00:08:02.280
And if I said mv square
equal to one Hartree,

00:08:02.280 --> 00:08:07.260
then I find that the
atomic unit of velocity

00:08:07.260 --> 00:08:09.080
is e squared over h-bar.

00:08:12.350 --> 00:08:18.960
But this turns out
to be alpha times c.

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:22.780
So again, what we find is alpha,
the fine-structure constant.

00:08:26.690 --> 00:08:30.630
Alpha is, of course,
dimensionless.

00:08:30.630 --> 00:08:37.809
It is 1/137.

00:08:37.809 --> 00:08:45.300
So therefore, we see that if the
velocity-- and this is actually

00:08:45.300 --> 00:08:48.200
the orbital velocity
of the 1s electron.

00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:52.190
If this is alpha
times c that confirms

00:08:52.190 --> 00:08:56.379
that the electron
non-relativistic.

00:08:56.379 --> 00:08:58.337
We have solved the
non-relativistic Schrodinger

00:08:58.337 --> 00:09:00.050
equation for it.

00:09:00.050 --> 00:09:05.800
And consistently, we find that
the velocity of the electron

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:11.072
is 1/137 of the speed of light.

00:09:11.072 --> 00:09:12.280
It's actually physics trivia.

00:09:12.280 --> 00:09:14.820
If somebody asks you
how fast is the electron

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:19.640
in the hydrogen atom, about
1% of the speed of light.

00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:23.825
Of course, if you had solved
the non-relativistic Schrodinger

00:09:23.825 --> 00:09:25.170
equation.

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:31.050
And you solve it for, let's
say, a naked uranium nucleus

00:09:31.050 --> 00:09:37.500
where z, the charge
of the nucleus, is 92,

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:42.390
then you find that this
fine-structure constant times

00:09:42.390 --> 00:09:43.930
z is on the order of unity.

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:48.490
You would find that the electron
moves at the speed of light.

00:09:48.490 --> 00:09:51.190
And then you realize, gosh,
I've solved the wrong equation.

00:09:51.190 --> 00:09:53.230
Because a non-relativistic
Schrodinger equation

00:09:53.230 --> 00:09:54.885
when the solution
is that something

00:09:54.885 --> 00:09:56.620
moves at the speed
of light, I'd better

00:09:56.620 --> 00:09:59.270
start with a different equation.

00:09:59.270 --> 00:10:01.590
But here, we find
we are consistent.

00:10:01.590 --> 00:10:11.830
An electron in the hydrogen
atom for low nuclear charges

00:10:11.830 --> 00:10:16.650
of a few hydrogen, helium,
and so on is non-relativistic.

00:10:16.650 --> 00:10:18.720
So let's just finish that.

00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:22.610
The electric field
is the electric field

00:10:22.610 --> 00:10:26.360
felt by the electron
which orbits

00:10:26.360 --> 00:10:30.210
the nucleus on the 1s shell.

00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:38.900
And this is 5.1 times 10 to
the 9 volts per centimeter.

00:10:38.900 --> 00:10:43.080
So everything I've constructed
here out of the three

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:45.990
fundamental
constants, e, m, and h

00:10:45.990 --> 00:10:48.720
are typical for the 1s
electron for the ground

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:50.280
state of hydrogen.

00:10:50.280 --> 00:10:53.460
We got the typical
lengths, the Bohr radius,

00:10:53.460 --> 00:10:57.710
the typical energy, the
Hartree, the typical velocity,

00:10:57.710 --> 00:11:04.770
which doesn't have a name,
and the electric field

00:11:04.770 --> 00:11:08.490
experienced by this electron.

00:11:08.490 --> 00:11:11.955
So let's now talk about alpha.

00:11:14.590 --> 00:11:17.720
So alpha is dimensionless.

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:25.990
It is, you know, if a constant
has dimension like h-bar,

00:11:25.990 --> 00:11:30.860
like c, actually the
value of it reflects

00:11:30.860 --> 00:11:32.550
our system of metrology.

00:11:32.550 --> 00:11:35.080
If you define the second
in a different way,

00:11:35.080 --> 00:11:36.790
h-bar will change.

00:11:36.790 --> 00:11:38.920
c will change.

00:11:38.920 --> 00:11:44.290
So a lot of constants are
not fundamental constants,

00:11:44.290 --> 00:11:46.910
being fundamental to
the physics at hand.

00:11:46.910 --> 00:11:49.300
They are more kind
of translating

00:11:49.300 --> 00:11:52.730
our metrological system
into the equations

00:11:52.730 --> 00:11:55.330
we use to describe our system.

00:11:55.330 --> 00:11:58.030
But if something
has no dimension,

00:11:58.030 --> 00:12:02.920
it is not related to a unit
like the kilogram or the second,

00:12:02.920 --> 00:12:07.000
it has really
fundamental importance.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:11.550
So, therefore, alpha is
the fundamental constant

00:12:11.550 --> 00:12:12.445
in atomic physics.

00:12:22.650 --> 00:12:27.660
And if you have a
fundamental constant,

00:12:27.660 --> 00:12:33.490
ultimately, there should
be a theory of everything

00:12:33.490 --> 00:12:39.680
which should ultimately
predict the value of alpha.

00:12:39.680 --> 00:12:49.880
Which, ultimately, we
predicted by a complete theory.

00:12:54.840 --> 00:13:03.900
So alpha, the fine-structure
constant, is smaller than 1.

00:13:03.900 --> 00:13:06.910
It's 1/137.

00:13:06.910 --> 00:13:10.840
And the fact that
alpha is smaller like 1

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:17.230
is often phrased in these words.

00:13:17.230 --> 00:13:20.990
That since alpha is
much smaller than 1

00:13:20.990 --> 00:13:29.230
that this implies the
electromagnetic interactions

00:13:29.230 --> 00:13:29.750
are weak.

00:13:34.820 --> 00:13:36.960
OK, I want to explain that.

00:13:36.960 --> 00:13:39.240
I mean, I've heard
this many, many times.

00:13:39.240 --> 00:13:42.240
But what does it mean
interactions are weak?

00:13:42.240 --> 00:13:46.300
So let me give you sort
of my, in 90 seconds,

00:13:46.300 --> 00:13:47.840
sort of my spiel on it.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:50.735
Why does alpha mean that the
electromagnetic interactions

00:13:50.735 --> 00:13:52.570
are weak?

00:13:52.570 --> 00:13:56.190
Well, we have to compare the
electromagnetic interaction

00:13:56.190 --> 00:13:57.210
to something else.

00:13:57.210 --> 00:14:01.120
And the result will be for
this situation I create,

00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:03.010
the electromagnetic
interactions are weak.

00:14:13.070 --> 00:14:15.160
Electromagnetic interactions
of the Coulomb field

00:14:15.160 --> 00:14:17.410
gets, of course,
stronger, and stronger,

00:14:17.410 --> 00:14:20.960
and stronger the closer you
move two charges together.

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:24.580
So what does it mean that the
Coulomb interaction is weak?

00:14:24.580 --> 00:14:27.750
Weaker compared to
strong interactions

00:14:27.750 --> 00:14:29.370
or other interactions.

00:14:29.370 --> 00:14:34.680
Well, let me try to
justify it as follows.

00:14:34.680 --> 00:14:41.210
We cannot go to epitary
small distances.

00:14:41.210 --> 00:14:42.870
We can do it in
classical physics,

00:14:42.870 --> 00:14:45.250
but not in quantum physics.

00:14:45.250 --> 00:14:47.390
So if you go to very
small distances,

00:14:47.390 --> 00:14:50.740
if you localize
particles very tightly,

00:14:50.740 --> 00:14:52.520
they have a lot of
momentum uncertainty.

00:14:52.520 --> 00:14:55.430
The momentum uncertainty
means energy uncertainty.

00:14:55.430 --> 00:14:57.650
And the energy
uncertainty may mean

00:14:57.650 --> 00:15:01.040
that we can create electrons
and positron pairs.

00:15:01.040 --> 00:15:04.230
So the moment we have
an energy uncertainty,

00:15:04.230 --> 00:15:08.390
by our definition of bringing
two particles close together,

00:15:08.390 --> 00:15:12.130
and this energy uncertainty
is larger than the rest mass,

00:15:12.130 --> 00:15:13.380
we have to be very careful.

00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:16.630
We can no longer use a
single particle description,

00:15:16.630 --> 00:15:18.980
or our concept of
single particle physics

00:15:18.980 --> 00:15:22.560
breaks down if you have
seen the particles prepared

00:15:22.560 --> 00:15:25.210
with an energy uncertainty,
which would spontaneously

00:15:25.210 --> 00:15:27.100
create more particles.

00:15:27.100 --> 00:15:35.740
So therefore, let me
postulate that our picture

00:15:35.740 --> 00:15:38.050
how we think about
those interactions,

00:15:38.050 --> 00:15:41.390
arranging two charges
and writing down

00:15:41.390 --> 00:15:43.430
what the Coulomb energy is.

00:15:43.430 --> 00:15:57.730
That if energy uncertainties
become on the order of the rest

00:15:57.730 --> 00:16:09.470
energy, then the concept of
single particles breaks down.

00:16:16.500 --> 00:16:18.490
Of course, that's not
the end of physics.

00:16:18.490 --> 00:16:22.420
You need now a field theory
for particles where particles

00:16:22.420 --> 00:16:23.923
are just excitations
in your field.

00:16:26.620 --> 00:16:28.290
But here in atomic
physics, you want

00:16:28.290 --> 00:16:31.550
to describe an electron
bound to a nucleus.

00:16:31.550 --> 00:16:33.870
And we want to use
those concepts.

00:16:33.870 --> 00:16:37.650
So let's just sort of say,
what does it mean with delta e

00:16:37.650 --> 00:16:39.680
is mc squared?

00:16:39.680 --> 00:16:42.620
Well, that means the
momentum uncertainty

00:16:42.620 --> 00:16:45.140
is on the order of mc.

00:16:45.140 --> 00:16:48.250
And with this
momentum uncertainty,

00:16:48.250 --> 00:16:56.140
I can localize particles
to within h-bar over mc.

00:16:56.140 --> 00:16:58.685
And this just turns
out to be the Compton

00:16:58.685 --> 00:17:01.490
radius of the electron.

00:17:01.490 --> 00:17:03.960
So, therefore, I
should be careful

00:17:03.960 --> 00:17:07.069
when I talk about the Coulomb
energy between particles

00:17:07.069 --> 00:17:10.030
if I would go closer
than the Compton radius.

00:17:10.030 --> 00:17:15.920
So, therefore, let me compare
now the Coulomb interaction

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:20.109
at the Compton radius
to something else.

00:17:20.109 --> 00:17:24.170
So these Coulomb energy is
e squared over the radius.

00:17:24.170 --> 00:17:26.270
The Compton radius.

00:17:26.270 --> 00:17:34.810
And this turns out to be
e squared, mc over h-bar.

00:17:34.810 --> 00:17:39.370
So unless I want to
get into quantum field

00:17:39.370 --> 00:17:49.230
theory of particles, before I
need a different description,

00:17:49.230 --> 00:17:52.210
the strongest
Coulomb interaction

00:17:52.210 --> 00:18:04.550
I can create by putting two
particles at the Compton radius

00:18:04.550 --> 00:18:06.080
is that.

00:18:06.080 --> 00:18:09.780
And I can now compare
this Coulomb interaction,

00:18:09.780 --> 00:18:16.020
the Coulomb energy, to the
rest energy, mc squared.

00:18:16.020 --> 00:18:22.660
And, well, if I take what I had
above, e squared mc over h-bar,

