00:27:58.750 --> 00:28:08.120
And in perturbation
theory, we simply take

00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:12.660
the wave function of the
simplified Hamiltonian

00:28:12.660 --> 00:28:14.495
and ask what is the
energy correction

00:28:14.495 --> 00:28:19.840
due to the fact that we
have a finite core size?

00:28:19.840 --> 00:28:29.230
Since the finite core is near
r equals 0 at the origin,

00:28:29.230 --> 00:28:33.230
we only need the scaling
of the wave function close

00:28:33.230 --> 00:28:35.410
to the origin.

00:28:35.410 --> 00:28:38.840
And this is r to the l.

00:28:38.840 --> 00:28:45.120
And we have n to the power
3/2, as we discussed last week.

00:28:45.120 --> 00:28:47.900
So our Hamiltonian is
now the Hamiltonian

00:28:47.900 --> 00:28:53.260
of the hydrogen atom
plus a perturbation term.

00:28:53.260 --> 00:28:56.520
And the perturbation
term is the derivation

00:28:56.520 --> 00:29:01.480
of the potentially experienced
by the outer electron,

00:29:01.480 --> 00:29:05.960
the deviation from a
pure Coulomb potential.

00:29:05.960 --> 00:29:15.020
So the energy correction,
en, is the expectation value

00:29:15.020 --> 00:29:22.860
of the hydrogenic wave
function with the perturbation

00:29:22.860 --> 00:29:23.930
Hamiltonian.

00:29:23.930 --> 00:29:26.550
And the only thing we have to
know about the perturbation

00:29:26.550 --> 00:29:31.600
Hamiltonian is that
this Hamiltonian is

00:29:31.600 --> 00:29:38.500
localized around the origin.

00:29:38.500 --> 00:29:43.610
And then we immediately
find because of the scaling

00:29:43.610 --> 00:29:49.590
of the wave function with
n that this is 1/n cubed.

00:29:52.550 --> 00:29:58.320
And it's proportional.

00:29:58.320 --> 00:30:04.990
And by factoring out
the Rydberg constant,

00:30:04.990 --> 00:30:08.480
I can parameterize
this matrix element

00:30:08.480 --> 00:30:14.840
with a quantity, delta l,
which is dimensionless.

00:30:14.840 --> 00:30:20.190
So that means that
the binding energy

00:30:20.190 --> 00:30:30.140
is the hydrogenic binding
energy plus this correction.

00:30:30.140 --> 00:30:33.510
And then to leading
order in delta

00:30:33.510 --> 00:30:40.980
l, it's identical
to this result.

00:30:40.980 --> 00:30:45.230
And this parameter,
delta l, which

00:30:45.230 --> 00:30:50.080
is characterizing a whole
Rydberg series for all n

00:30:50.080 --> 00:30:53.940
values for given l, this is
called the quantum defect.

00:30:56.730 --> 00:30:59.260
So people realized early
on in the early days

00:30:59.260 --> 00:31:01.600
of quantum mechanics
before they understood it

00:31:01.600 --> 00:31:05.480
that the spectrum of
many atoms followed

00:31:05.480 --> 00:31:09.790
a formula which was not
1/n squared is hydrogen.

00:31:09.790 --> 00:31:14.070
It was 1n minus delta l squared.

00:31:14.070 --> 00:31:15.470
They didn't understand it.

00:31:15.470 --> 00:31:17.490
But this is, of course,
now the derivation.

00:31:26.620 --> 00:31:33.560
There are many other
derivations which

00:31:33.560 --> 00:31:38.040
you may enjoy reading about
it in our atomic physics wiki.

00:31:38.040 --> 00:31:42.340
There's a derivation using
the semi-classical approach

00:31:42.340 --> 00:31:44.810
and using the very
nice physical picture

00:31:44.810 --> 00:31:50.130
that an electron, when it
comes close to the core,

00:31:50.130 --> 00:31:52.590
experiences scattering
phase shift.

00:31:52.590 --> 00:31:55.020
And this scattering phase
shift is directly related

00:31:55.020 --> 00:31:56.850
to the quantum defect.

00:31:56.850 --> 00:32:01.020
Or you can make a
model Hamiltonian

00:32:01.020 --> 00:32:06.930
which is exactly solvable where
the perturbation Hamiltonian is

00:32:06.930 --> 00:32:10.580
not completely
localized at the core.

00:32:10.580 --> 00:32:14.100
But it's proportional
to 1/r squared.

00:32:14.100 --> 00:32:16.230
And then you can
exactly solve it

00:32:16.230 --> 00:32:18.200
because you have
already a term which

00:32:18.200 --> 00:32:20.860
is 1/r squared in your
Schrodinger equation.

00:32:20.860 --> 00:32:22.730
Which is the centrifugal term.

00:32:22.730 --> 00:32:25.790
So therefore, the
perturbation is only

00:32:25.790 --> 00:32:28.580
redefining the centrifugal term.

00:32:28.580 --> 00:32:31.246
It's redefining what l is.

00:32:31.246 --> 00:32:32.995
And eventually, you
can solve it directly.

