00:33:43.880 --> 00:33:46.990
you're supposed to know.

00:33:46.990 --> 00:33:52.270
So the spectroscopic
notation, the term designation

00:33:52.270 --> 00:33:58.170
focuses on the fact that if
you have an isolated atom,

00:33:58.170 --> 00:34:02.850
we have angular
momentum conservation.

00:34:02.850 --> 00:34:10.927
And so we have at least
two quantum numbers.

00:34:10.927 --> 00:34:13.010
Which are sometimes also
two good quantum numbers.

00:34:13.010 --> 00:34:14.940
We have some approximate
quantum numbers

00:34:14.940 --> 00:34:19.540
where we have additional terms
which break certain symmetries.

00:34:19.540 --> 00:34:24.179
But an isolated atom
lives in isotropic space.

00:34:24.179 --> 00:34:30.070
The total angular momentum
of this atom is conserved.

00:34:30.070 --> 00:34:31.830
It's absolutely conserved.

00:34:31.830 --> 00:34:34.150
It's absolutely
good quantum number.

00:34:34.150 --> 00:34:37.739
And the good quantum numbers is
the total angular momentum, j,

00:34:37.739 --> 00:34:39.510
and its protection energy.

00:34:43.989 --> 00:34:54.040
So in the language of atomic
physics, we call j a level.

00:34:54.040 --> 00:34:55.800
It's different from states.

00:34:55.800 --> 00:35:05.050
So one level has now 2j
plus 1 sub-levels or states.

00:35:08.760 --> 00:35:10.850
So usually when we
talk about a level,

00:35:10.850 --> 00:35:14.950
we assume the level
has degeneracies

00:35:14.950 --> 00:35:17.340
because there is the
Mj quantum number.

00:35:21.060 --> 00:35:27.030
So j, you're talking about
electronic structure.

00:35:27.030 --> 00:35:36.700
So j can have, when we
have an isolated atom,

00:35:36.700 --> 00:35:40.275
can have contributions
from several electrons.

00:35:51.040 --> 00:35:53.930
It can have contributions
and these electrons

00:35:53.930 --> 00:36:04.990
can contribute through
spin, s, and orbital angular

00:36:04.990 --> 00:36:06.128
momentum, l.

00:36:13.950 --> 00:36:17.990
In many situations,
especially with alkali atoms,

00:36:17.990 --> 00:36:21.050
the inner core is
completely field shell.

00:36:21.050 --> 00:36:23.780
There is no s, no l
from the inner electrons

00:36:23.780 --> 00:36:24.857
which contribute.

00:36:24.857 --> 00:36:26.940
And all the contribution
with the angular momentum

00:36:26.940 --> 00:36:28.190
comes from the outer electron.

00:36:31.220 --> 00:36:38.420
Especially for
the lighter atoms.

00:36:38.420 --> 00:36:41.800
The non-relativistic atoms.

00:36:41.800 --> 00:36:49.390
The different electrons
undergo ls copying.

00:36:49.390 --> 00:36:53.080
In other words, if you
have multiple electrons,

00:36:53.080 --> 00:36:58.325
their orbital angular
momentum couple up

00:36:58.325 --> 00:37:01.760
to the total orbital
angular momentum, l.

00:37:01.760 --> 00:37:08.290
And all the spins couple
up to the total spin, s.

00:37:08.290 --> 00:37:14.120
So therefore, before we
introduce spin orbit copying,

00:37:14.120 --> 00:37:16.070
l is a good quantum number.

00:37:16.070 --> 00:37:17.800
s is a good quantum number.

00:37:17.800 --> 00:37:22.500
And then they couple to
a good quantum number, j.

00:37:22.500 --> 00:37:26.500
Of course, once l and s
couple to j, orbital and spin

00:37:26.500 --> 00:37:31.260
angular momentum precess around
the total angular momentum.

00:37:31.260 --> 00:37:32.910
Anyway, I just
want to say when I

00:37:32.910 --> 00:37:36.326
talk about j, what are
possible ingredients?

00:37:40.030 --> 00:37:45.460
So let's assume we have an
atom which has total angular

00:37:45.460 --> 00:37:47.520
momentum, j.

00:37:47.520 --> 00:37:52.337
And which is the sum of orbital
angular momentum and spin

00:37:52.337 --> 00:37:53.045
angular momentum.

00:37:55.800 --> 00:38:10.020
And then in this case, we
use a term designation.

00:38:10.020 --> 00:38:21.250
A level is designated
by a term which

00:38:21.250 --> 00:38:28.030
is written as l, the value
of orbital angular momentum.

00:38:28.030 --> 00:38:34.420
The spin multiplicity, 2s
plus 1 is an upper left index.

00:38:34.420 --> 00:38:36.780
And a lower right index is j.

00:38:41.130 --> 00:38:50.190
And of course if l is 0,
we use the letter s, p, d.

00:38:50.190 --> 00:38:54.000
This is sort of the
historic letter designation

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:56.680
for l equals 0, 1 and 2.

00:39:04.140 --> 00:39:07.040
So in other words, if you have
an atom where the total angular

00:39:07.040 --> 00:39:10.310
momentum is composed of orbital
angular momentum and spin,

00:39:10.310 --> 00:39:12.310
you can always
write this symbol.

00:39:12.310 --> 00:39:15.700
And this symbol is
the term designation

00:39:15.700 --> 00:39:20.190
which characterizes the state,
the ground state or an excited

00:39:20.190 --> 00:39:21.250
state of your atom.

00:39:27.130 --> 00:39:49.270
If you have the hydrogenic
atom, often you precede the term

00:39:49.270 --> 00:39:58.000
by the principal
quantum number, n.

00:40:01.910 --> 00:40:05.920
So let me give you an example.

00:40:05.920 --> 00:40:15.060
If you have the sodium atom, the
outer electron has n equals 3.

00:40:15.060 --> 00:40:18.670
It has 0 orbital
angular momentum.

00:40:18.670 --> 00:40:20.420
It has spin 1/2.

00:40:20.420 --> 00:40:23.360
And 2s plus 1 is 2.

00:40:23.360 --> 00:40:30.710
And the total angular
momentum is 1/2.

00:40:30.710 --> 00:40:34.860
If you go to the first excited
state, you're still in n

00:40:34.860 --> 00:40:36.080
equals 3.

00:40:36.080 --> 00:40:38.970
But you have promoted the
electron from an s state

00:40:38.970 --> 00:40:40.690
to p state.

00:40:40.690 --> 00:40:43.260
So, therefore, the
orbital angular momentum

00:40:43.260 --> 00:40:47.330
is now 1 designated by p.

00:40:47.330 --> 00:40:50.190
The spin is still spin 1/2.

00:40:50.190 --> 00:40:54.780
But now orbital angular
momentum of 1 and spin 1/2

00:40:54.780 --> 00:40:58.450
can form a total
angular momentum

00:40:58.450 --> 00:41:02.915
which can either be 1/2 or 3/2.

00:41:07.240 --> 00:41:14.100
So if you're asked what is the
state you prepare your atom in,

00:41:14.100 --> 00:41:18.520
you would give it a
symbol 3 doublet p 1/2.

00:41:18.520 --> 00:41:20.220
And I've explained
to you what it means.

00:41:23.920 --> 00:41:26.090
There is one addition.

00:41:26.090 --> 00:41:36.120
And sometimes you want
to not just mention

00:41:36.120 --> 00:41:39.570
what is the principle quantum
number of the outer electrons.

00:41:39.570 --> 00:41:43.675
Sometimes you want to specify
the whole configuration.

00:41:54.760 --> 00:41:59.570
So this would mean you want to
sort of build up the electron

00:41:59.570 --> 00:42:04.750
shell and say that I have
two electrons in 1s, two

00:42:04.750 --> 00:42:11.280
electrons in 2s, one
electron in 2p, and so on.

00:42:11.280 --> 00:42:18.910
So you use, I think this
would now be beryllium atom?

00:42:23.400 --> 00:42:25.870
1s.

00:42:25.870 --> 00:42:29.920
So 1s is hydrogen,
1s2 is helium.

00:42:29.920 --> 00:42:32.876
Then we go to lithium.

00:42:32.876 --> 00:42:34.727
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] is boron.

00:42:34.727 --> 00:42:35.810
PROFESSOR: It's boron, no?

00:42:35.810 --> 00:42:37.660
OK, so this would be boron.

00:42:37.660 --> 00:42:42.010
So what we use is here
we use the products.

00:42:42.010 --> 00:42:52.120
We use products of
symbols n, l, m.

00:42:52.120 --> 00:42:56.600
So to come back to
the example of sodium,

00:42:56.600 --> 00:43:00.220
so sodium is filled up.

00:43:00.220 --> 00:43:03.690
As in the first shells.

00:43:03.690 --> 00:43:05.840
So it's 2p6.

00:43:05.840 --> 00:43:10.230
And then we have one electron,
the outer electron in 3s.

00:43:14.350 --> 00:43:17.470
However, let me point
out that this way

00:43:17.470 --> 00:43:20.610
to specify the
configuration strongly

00:43:20.610 --> 00:43:23.420
depends on a hydrogenic model.

00:43:23.420 --> 00:43:27.380
It assumes that the electrons
are non-interacting.

00:43:27.380 --> 00:43:30.170
And is, therefore,
an approximation.

00:43:30.170 --> 00:43:33.290
In contrast, the
term designation

00:43:33.290 --> 00:43:38.342
with a total angular
momentum is always exact.

00:43:38.342 --> 00:43:40.050
Well, at least the
total angular momentum

00:43:40.050 --> 00:43:41.270
is an exact quantum number.

00:43:41.270 --> 00:43:43.500
Whereas the
configuration is based

00:43:43.500 --> 00:43:47.630
on the independent
electron approximation

00:43:47.630 --> 00:43:49.540
in hydrogenic orbits.

00:43:49.540 --> 00:43:52.680
And usually when
you have a real atom

00:43:52.680 --> 00:43:55.770
and you calculate
with high precision

00:43:55.770 --> 00:43:58.530
what the electronic
wave function is,

00:43:58.530 --> 00:44:02.640
you find actually that total
many-body wave function

00:44:02.640 --> 00:44:05.610
is a superposition of
many such configurations.

00:44:05.610 --> 00:44:08.780
But as long as one
configuration is dominant,

00:44:08.780 --> 00:44:11.000
this configuration
designation makes sense.

00:44:16.650 --> 00:44:17.330
Any questions?

00:44:21.910 --> 00:44:26.060
OK, so we come back
to the hydrogen atom

00:44:26.060 --> 00:44:32.370
when we discuss smaller
features of the energy levels.

00:44:32.370 --> 00:44:35.530
Fine structure, hyperfine
structure, and so on.

00:44:35.530 --> 00:44:39.890
But in our discussion of
electronic energies, that's all

00:44:39.890 --> 00:44:44.010
I want to say about
one electron atoms.

00:44:44.010 --> 00:44:49.710
So let's now proceed and
discuss the helium atom.

00:44:54.600 --> 00:45:00.580
So we want to understand now
what are the new effects when

00:45:00.580 --> 00:45:03.090
we have not only one
electron, but two electrons.

00:45:10.150 --> 00:45:11.030
And don't worry.

00:45:11.030 --> 00:45:13.700
We are not proceeding to
three, four, five electrons.

00:45:13.700 --> 00:45:16.340
I think to go from one
to two, we actually

00:45:16.340 --> 00:45:18.730
capture the most
important state.

00:45:18.730 --> 00:45:22.100
Namely, the interaction between
the two electrons and what

00:45:22.100 --> 00:45:23.345
the results of that is.

00:45:26.930 --> 00:45:31.550
For the helium atom, there
are some excellent treatments

00:45:31.550 --> 00:45:35.330
in standard textbooks
of quantum mechanics.

00:45:35.330 --> 00:45:42.410
One is the famous
quantum mechanic

00:45:42.410 --> 00:45:44.930
text by Cohen-Tannoudji et al.

00:45:47.690 --> 00:45:54.700
But also the text
of Gasiorowicz.

00:46:03.410 --> 00:46:07.870
The reason why I have added the
helium atom to the curriculum

00:46:07.870 --> 00:46:11.930
is because it is a
simple system where

00:46:11.930 --> 00:46:16.180
we can discuss singlet
and triplet states.

00:46:16.180 --> 00:46:19.220
And singlet and
triplet configuration

00:46:19.220 --> 00:46:24.810
is important for population
of inoptical lattices

00:46:24.810 --> 00:46:26.690
for quantum magnetism and such.

00:46:26.690 --> 00:46:29.510
Actually, you can say if
you have two electrons

00:46:29.510 --> 00:46:33.080
and they align in a triplet
state or a singlet state,

00:46:33.080 --> 00:46:34.910
one you can say
is ferromagnetic.

00:46:34.910 --> 00:46:37.430
The other one is paired
and antiferromagnetic.

00:46:37.430 --> 00:46:41.740
It's the simplest example
where we can discuss magnetism.

00:46:41.740 --> 00:46:45.130
So that's my motivation why
I want you to know something

00:46:45.130 --> 00:46:46.410
about the helium atom.

00:46:49.630 --> 00:46:58.810
So, therefore, let's now
discuss energy levels of helium.

00:47:09.740 --> 00:47:20.220
And let's just start with
the most basic model.

00:47:20.220 --> 00:47:24.400
The helium atom has two charges.

00:47:24.400 --> 00:47:28.740
So if you regard it
as a hydrogen problem

00:47:28.740 --> 00:47:36.700
and we put two electrons
into the 1s state,

00:47:36.700 --> 00:47:43.220
we would expect that based
on the hydrogenic model

00:47:43.220 --> 00:47:49.870
that the binding energy
of that is, per electron,

00:47:49.870 --> 00:47:53.450
is the Rydberg energy
as in hydrogen.

00:47:53.450 --> 00:47:58.520
But now we have to scale it with
z squared, the nuclear charge.

00:47:58.520 --> 00:48:00.890
And this gives us a factor of 4.

00:48:00.890 --> 00:48:05.530
So we would expect that per
electron, the binding energy

00:48:05.530 --> 00:48:10.095
in the more simple hydrogenic
model is 54 electron volt.

00:48:12.750 --> 00:48:22.770
So that would mean that the
binding energy of the ground

00:48:22.770 --> 00:48:29.220
state is minus
108 electron volt.

00:48:37.050 --> 00:48:45.420
However, the
experimental result is

00:48:45.420 --> 00:48:50.610
that it's only 79 electron volt.

00:48:50.610 --> 00:49:01.140
So we find that there is a
big discrepancy of 29 electron

00:49:01.140 --> 00:49:02.230
volt.

00:49:02.230 --> 00:49:05.390
Which is really huge.

00:49:05.390 --> 00:49:10.480
So what is responsible
for this big discrepancy?

00:49:10.480 --> 00:49:12.810
Well, what we have
neglected, of course,

00:49:12.810 --> 00:49:15.250
is the interaction
between the two electrons.

00:49:34.730 --> 00:49:39.810
So we can fix that
in the simplest way

00:49:39.810 --> 00:49:43.380
by keeping the wave function
from the hydrogenic model.

00:49:43.380 --> 00:49:48.920
But now calculating the
electronic energies,

00:49:48.920 --> 00:49:54.200
the electron-electron
energy, by using

00:49:54.200 --> 00:49:59.066
the electron-electron
interaction as a perturbation

00:49:59.066 --> 00:49:59.565
operator.

00:50:03.510 --> 00:50:08.530
So we still use as the wave
function for the ground

00:50:08.530 --> 00:50:15.890
state, electron 1
in the 1s state.

00:50:15.890 --> 00:50:20.460
So 1-0-0 is a designation for n,
l, m for the hydrogenic quantum

00:50:20.460 --> 00:50:21.550
numbers.

00:50:21.550 --> 00:50:24.640
And we assume that the
ground state is simply

00:50:24.640 --> 00:50:29.220
the product of two
electrons in the 1s state.

00:50:29.220 --> 00:50:34.280
So if I calculate for
this perturbation operator

00:50:34.280 --> 00:50:38.970
the expectation value
with this ground state,

00:50:38.970 --> 00:50:46.470
we find that there is an
energy correction which

00:50:46.470 --> 00:50:52.010
is 34 electron volt.

00:50:52.010 --> 00:51:00.680
So this removes most
of the discrepancy.

00:51:10.610 --> 00:51:16.390
You can improve on it by
a variation wave function

00:51:16.390 --> 00:51:20.270
if you use hydrogenic
eigenfunctions as your tile

00:51:20.270 --> 00:51:21.710
wave function.

00:51:21.710 --> 00:51:25.520
But you are now calculating
those hydrogenic wave functions

00:51:25.520 --> 00:51:31.640
not for nuclear charge 2, but
in nuclear charge c star, which

00:51:31.640 --> 00:51:33.900
you keep as a
variation of parameter.

00:51:33.900 --> 00:51:39.890
You find that you find
even better wave functions.

00:51:39.890 --> 00:51:42.830
And you can remove
2/3 of these remaining

00:51:42.830 --> 00:51:45.570
discrepancy of five
electron volts.

00:51:45.570 --> 00:51:49.879
This variational wave
function is left to you

00:51:49.879 --> 00:51:50.920
as a homework assignment.

00:52:05.540 --> 00:52:09.155
So where z is z
equals 2 is replaced

00:52:09.155 --> 00:52:11.530
by a variation of parameter.

00:52:11.530 --> 00:52:13.540
Anyway, that's all
I want to tell you

00:52:13.540 --> 00:52:17.550
about the ground
state of helium.

00:52:17.550 --> 00:52:20.280
It's pretty much
finding a wave function

00:52:20.280 --> 00:52:23.460
which correctly captures
the Coulomb energies.

00:52:23.460 --> 00:52:28.900
The interaction between
the two electrons.

00:52:28.900 --> 00:52:31.370
But what is much
more interesting,

00:52:31.370 --> 00:52:33.310
and this is what
I want to focus on

00:52:33.310 --> 00:52:35.370
for the rest of this
lecture, is what

00:52:35.370 --> 00:52:39.200
happens in the excited state.

00:52:39.200 --> 00:52:40.800
Before I do that,
let me just tell you

00:52:40.800 --> 00:52:42.540
what we just discussed.

00:52:42.540 --> 00:52:45.300
So we have to this
hydrogenic estimate

00:52:45.300 --> 00:52:51.840
and eventually the Coulomb
energy raises the energy level

00:52:51.840 --> 00:52:55.520
to what we have just discussed.

00:52:55.520 --> 00:52:58.120
But, you know, as the ground
state has no degeneracy.

00:52:58.120 --> 00:53:01.970
And so we all talk about
quantitative shifts.

00:53:01.970 --> 00:53:05.240
However, when we go
to the excited state,

00:53:05.240 --> 00:53:07.930
we will find the degeneracies.

00:53:07.930 --> 00:53:09.800
And degeneracies are
much more interesting

00:53:09.800 --> 00:53:12.960
because something which
was degenerate can split.

00:53:12.960 --> 00:53:14.410
You have two different terms.

00:53:14.410 --> 00:53:16.910
So suddenly there
is richer physics.

00:53:16.910 --> 00:53:21.930
So, therefore, we want to
discuss now the excited state.

00:53:21.930 --> 00:53:28.830
So starting again with
the hydrogenic model.

00:53:28.830 --> 00:53:32.170
In hydrogen, the
2s and 2p state are

00:53:32.170 --> 00:53:37.420
degenerate so we have two
configurations contributing

00:53:37.420 --> 00:53:38.540
to the same energy.

00:53:38.540 --> 00:53:40.880
1s 2s and 1s 2p.

00:53:46.200 --> 00:53:49.620
The binding energy in
the hydrogenic model

00:53:49.620 --> 00:53:51.900
is a quarter of a Rydberg.

00:53:51.900 --> 00:53:55.450
Rydberg over n square and ns2.

00:53:55.450 --> 00:53:57.900
We have to scale it by z square.

00:53:57.900 --> 00:54:04.480
And we find 13.6 electron volt.

00:54:04.480 --> 00:54:06.880
But now what happens
is that we have

00:54:06.880 --> 00:54:14.040
to introduce the Coulomb
energy between the electrons.

00:54:14.040 --> 00:54:22.250
And if you do that, it shifts
up the levels in different ways.

00:54:22.250 --> 00:54:24.860
So this is 1s, 2s.

00:54:24.860 --> 00:54:26.050
This is 1s, 2p.

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:32.110
So why is this different?

00:54:54.870 --> 00:54:56.780
Well, you can say the following.

00:55:08.970 --> 00:55:10.370
You have two electrons.

00:55:10.370 --> 00:55:13.400
And you have the helium nucleus.

00:55:13.400 --> 00:55:18.630
And you first put
in the 1s electron.

00:55:18.630 --> 00:55:22.410
And now the second electron
when it is in a p state,

00:55:22.410 --> 00:55:25.490
in a 2p state, it's further out.

00:55:25.490 --> 00:55:28.110
And it pretty much
experiences out

00:55:28.110 --> 00:55:31.240
there the charge of
the helium nucleus

00:55:31.240 --> 00:55:33.840
shielded by the 1s electron.

00:55:33.840 --> 00:55:37.330
And, therefore, it sees
in effect a smaller

00:55:37.330 --> 00:55:39.450
nuclear charge.

00:55:39.450 --> 00:55:43.950
Whereas, the two s
electron penetrates deeper.

00:55:43.950 --> 00:55:46.450
Gets closer to the
nucleus and will still

00:55:46.450 --> 00:55:49.990
realize that the nucleus
has a charge of 2.

00:55:49.990 --> 00:55:51.860
And not a shielded charge.

00:55:51.860 --> 00:55:56.190
So, therefore, you would expect
that the shielding effect

00:55:56.190 --> 00:55:59.580
due to the innermost
electron is more important,

00:55:59.580 --> 00:56:02.530
has a bigger effect
for the 2p electron

00:56:02.530 --> 00:56:03.665
then for the 2s electron.

00:56:07.610 --> 00:56:10.000
So let me just write that down.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:17.830
So the 2p electron it
sees a shielded nucleus.

00:56:22.700 --> 00:56:26.260
In other words, what
it experiences more

00:56:26.260 --> 00:56:31.500
as an inner core, the Coulomb
potential of helium plus.

00:56:31.500 --> 00:56:33.945
And not so much
of helium 2 plus.

00:56:41.280 --> 00:56:45.060
This is due to the 1s electron.

00:56:45.060 --> 00:56:53.000
And, therefore, the 2p electron
has a smaller binding energy.

00:56:55.610 --> 00:57:07.900
It's actually comparable
to the binding energy

00:57:07.900 --> 00:57:09.855
of the 2p state in hydrogen.

00:57:12.840 --> 00:57:15.348
Which is on the order
of 4 electron volt.

00:57:19.220 --> 00:57:32.690
And this effect is
smaller for the 2s state.

00:57:36.050 --> 00:57:37.900
So let's go back to
the energy diagram.

00:57:42.980 --> 00:57:51.020
So we have now the situation
which I just described.

00:57:51.020 --> 00:57:54.110
We have two degenerate
configurations

00:57:54.110 --> 00:57:56.020
for in the hydrogen model.

00:57:56.020 --> 00:58:01.320
And when we add in Coulomb
energy between the electrons,

00:58:01.320 --> 00:58:04.400
there is quite a big splitting
of several electron volts.

00:58:08.780 --> 00:58:13.832
But now, each label
undergoes further splitting.

00:58:13.832 --> 00:58:15.290
And this is what
I want to discuss.

00:58:17.800 --> 00:58:20.010
So we are still sorting
out just the preliminaries.

00:58:20.010 --> 00:58:22.120
What I really want
to discuss with you

00:58:22.120 --> 00:58:23.920
is the singlet
and triplet thing.

00:58:23.920 --> 00:58:27.090
But now we are there
where we can do it.

00:58:27.090 --> 00:58:32.420
So if you have a
configuration with 1s, 2s,

00:58:32.420 --> 00:58:37.330
there are two possibilities
for the total angular momentum.

00:58:37.330 --> 00:58:39.500
Two electrons in
an s state, there

00:58:39.500 --> 00:58:41.090
is no orbital angular momentum.

00:58:41.090 --> 00:58:43.200
But there are two spins, 1/2.

00:58:43.200 --> 00:58:47.130
And they can add up to
1 or can add up to 0.

00:58:47.130 --> 00:58:53.120
So, therefore, we will
have two different terms.

00:58:53.120 --> 00:58:57.760
One is singlet s0.

00:58:57.760 --> 00:59:01.750
And one is triplet s1.

00:59:01.750 --> 00:59:05.840
And this splitting
is 0.8 electron volt.

00:59:05.840 --> 00:59:08.800
And this is what we want to
discuss in the following.

00:59:08.800 --> 00:59:12.080
For completeness, but
the physics is similar,

00:59:12.080 --> 00:59:18.270
let me mention that the
1s, 2p state also gives

00:59:18.270 --> 00:59:19.780
rise to two terms.

00:59:19.780 --> 00:59:24.406
We have now the total
orbital angular momentum, p.

00:59:24.406 --> 00:59:26.610
Orbital angular momentum of 1.

00:59:26.610 --> 00:59:30.350
The spin angular
momentum is 0 or 1.

00:59:30.350 --> 00:59:33.080
So we have singlet and triplet.

00:59:33.080 --> 00:59:43.400
And the total angular
momentum is 1 in this case.

00:59:43.400 --> 00:59:49.410
Or in this case, 2, 1, or 0.

00:59:49.410 --> 00:59:53.240
And the splitting
in this situation

00:59:53.240 --> 00:59:57.240
is also on the order of a
fraction of an electron volt.

01:00:00.400 --> 01:00:02.840
So what we want
to understand now

01:00:02.840 --> 01:00:10.090
is why do we observe a splitting
between those two levels

01:00:10.090 --> 01:00:12.990
which seems to
depend on the spin?

01:00:12.990 --> 01:00:16.290
How can the spin
cause a splitting?

01:00:16.290 --> 01:00:23.230
Because the spin so far has not
appeared in our Hamiltonian.

01:00:23.230 --> 01:00:24.920
We rarely have a
Hamiltonian which

01:00:24.920 --> 01:00:26.970
has only the Coulomb energy.

01:00:26.970 --> 01:00:30.050
And the spin is not part of it.

01:00:30.050 --> 01:00:31.660
So we don't have
a magnetic field

01:00:31.660 --> 01:00:34.640
to which the magnetic momentum
of the spin would couple.

01:00:34.640 --> 01:00:38.680
And also we have not yet
introduced spin orbit coupling.

01:00:38.680 --> 01:00:41.620
But if this is on your
mind, take it off your mind.

01:00:41.620 --> 01:00:45.710
Spin orbit coupling is a
much, much smaller effect.

01:00:45.710 --> 01:00:48.350
Energies on the order
of 1 electron volt,

01:00:48.350 --> 01:00:51.510
you just cannot get from
spin orbit coupling.

01:00:51.510 --> 01:00:54.820
Spin orbit coupling is smaller
than electronic energies,

01:00:54.820 --> 01:00:58.050
as I will explain
to you on Friday,

01:00:58.050 --> 01:01:00.470
is smaller by the fine
structure constant.

01:01:00.470 --> 01:01:05.010
So the typical scale
for spin orbit coupling

01:01:05.010 --> 01:01:10.600
is maybe 10 or 100
million electron volt.

01:01:10.600 --> 01:01:12.880
It's much smaller.

01:01:12.880 --> 01:01:15.610
So, therefore, we
want to understand now

01:01:15.610 --> 01:01:18.890
why do we have a spin
dependent energy.

01:01:18.890 --> 01:01:23.140
Also we haven't coupled at this
point the spin to any field.

01:01:29.910 --> 01:01:35.680
OK, so we are focusing
now on the splitting.

01:01:44.030 --> 01:01:50.980
So we have the 1s,
2s configuration.

01:01:50.980 --> 01:01:53.650
We get two terms,
as I just discussed.

01:01:57.540 --> 01:02:02.180
One is singlet and
one is triplet.

01:02:04.720 --> 01:02:11.550
And still using the
hydrogenic model

01:02:11.550 --> 01:02:14.240
of non-interacting
electrons, we want

01:02:14.240 --> 01:02:17.290
to write down the wave function.

01:02:17.290 --> 01:02:22.010
So the wave function
of the twin electrons

01:02:22.010 --> 01:02:28.870
is we have one electron
in the 1s state.

01:02:28.870 --> 01:02:36.140
We have one electron
in the 2s state.

01:02:36.140 --> 01:02:40.720
But now since we
have fermionic atoms,

01:02:40.720 --> 01:02:46.030
we have to correctly
symmetrize it.

01:02:46.030 --> 01:02:54.390
So whether we want the symmetric
or antisymmetric combination,

01:02:54.390 --> 01:02:58.300
we exchange the two electrons.

01:02:58.300 --> 01:03:03.375
So now we have r2 and
r2 in reverse order.

01:03:07.410 --> 01:03:17.060
Of course, the total wave
function for two fermions

01:03:17.060 --> 01:03:19.880
has to be antisymmetric.

01:03:19.880 --> 01:03:23.740
But the total wave function is
the product of the spatial wave

01:03:23.740 --> 01:03:28.770
function which I just wrote down
times the spin wave function.

01:03:28.770 --> 01:03:36.330
The spin wave function can be
antisymmetric and symmetric.

01:03:36.330 --> 01:03:41.460
And the antisymmetric
spin wave function

01:03:41.460 --> 01:03:44.270
has to combine with the
symmetric spatial wave

01:03:44.270 --> 01:03:47.010
function, and vice
versa, to make sure

01:03:47.010 --> 01:03:50.080
that the total wave
function is antisymmetric.

01:03:50.080 --> 01:03:54.120
And the correct
description for fermions.

01:03:54.120 --> 01:03:56.940
The designation here,
symmetric and antisymmetric

01:03:56.940 --> 01:04:02.100
for the total wave function
reflects the spatial part.

01:04:02.100 --> 01:04:04.690
The total wave function, of
course, including the spin wave

01:04:04.690 --> 01:04:06.065
function is always
antisymmetric.

01:04:12.900 --> 01:04:20.250
OK, so we have two
wave functions.

01:04:20.250 --> 01:04:27.210
One has a symmetric
spatial wave function.

01:04:31.410 --> 01:04:34.960
The other one, an antisymmetric.

01:04:34.960 --> 01:04:38.280
The symmetric
spatial wave function

01:04:38.280 --> 01:04:44.120
has an antisymmetric
spin wave function.

01:04:48.070 --> 01:04:53.650
And that means we
have s equals 0.

01:04:53.650 --> 01:04:57.040
That's up, down, minus
down, up is antisymmetric.

01:04:57.040 --> 01:04:59.730
Where as the
antisymmetric spatial

01:04:59.730 --> 01:05:04.550
wave function goes together
with the symmetric spin wave

01:05:04.550 --> 01:05:08.040
function s equals 1.

01:05:08.040 --> 01:05:10.900
So this is the situation
which gives rise

01:05:10.900 --> 01:05:19.720
to that triplet s1 term.

01:05:19.720 --> 01:05:22.810
And this here is
the singlet s0 term.

01:05:27.390 --> 01:05:28.330
OK.

01:05:28.330 --> 01:05:31.996
As long as we have
non-interacting electron,

01:05:31.996 --> 01:05:36.300
the two wave functions
are degenerate.

01:05:36.300 --> 01:05:44.200
But now we want to bring in the
Coulomb energy between the two

01:05:44.200 --> 01:05:47.460
electrons which we had
already discussed before.

01:06:17.590 --> 01:06:27.720
And if you calculate the energy
using this as a perturbation

01:06:27.720 --> 01:06:32.880
operator, well, remember the
wave function had two parts.

01:06:32.880 --> 01:06:37.670
It was 100, r1, 200, r2.

01:06:37.670 --> 01:06:41.570
And the part where our 1
and our 2 were flipped.

01:06:41.570 --> 01:06:46.730
And now if we have the wave
function, the perturbation

01:06:46.730 --> 01:06:51.500
operator, we get a
total of 4 terms.

01:06:51.500 --> 01:06:52.310
2 times 2.

01:06:52.310 --> 01:06:55.220
We have to sort of x it out.

01:06:55.220 --> 01:07:01.770
And we will then have the
sort of diagonal parts.

01:07:01.770 --> 01:07:04.450
And we have the parts
which are off diagonal.

01:07:04.450 --> 01:07:13.720
And for the off
diagonal parts, it

01:07:13.720 --> 01:07:16.120
matters whether we had
the plus or minus sign.

01:07:16.120 --> 01:07:19.350
You know, if you have plus,
plus and minus, minus,

01:07:19.350 --> 01:07:20.880
you give a positive
contribution.

01:07:20.880 --> 01:07:24.590
But if you connect
the wave function

01:07:24.590 --> 01:07:32.700
before and after the
operator, plus with minus,

01:07:32.700 --> 01:07:33.880
we get minus signs.

01:07:33.880 --> 01:07:36.920
So in other words, we
have one contribution

01:07:36.920 --> 01:07:38.600
where it doesn't
matter whether we

01:07:38.600 --> 01:07:40.690
have the symmetric or
antisymmetric spatial wave

01:07:40.690 --> 01:07:41.460
function.

01:07:41.460 --> 01:07:44.094
But then we have
another term where

01:07:44.094 --> 01:07:46.510
it matters whether we have the
symmetric and antisymmetric

01:07:46.510 --> 01:07:47.120
wave function.

01:07:47.120 --> 01:07:49.940
That's where the plus or minus
sign from the symmetrized wave

01:07:49.940 --> 01:07:51.710
function appears.

01:07:51.710 --> 01:07:55.350
So we have two contributions
now to the energy correction.

01:07:55.350 --> 01:07:59.010
One is independent of
the spin wave function

01:07:59.010 --> 01:08:01.930
whether we have the symmetric
or antisymmetric configuration.

01:08:01.930 --> 01:08:03.430
The other one is not.

01:08:03.430 --> 01:08:06.190
The first term is called
the Coulomb energy.

01:08:06.190 --> 01:08:09.090
The second term is called
the exchange energy.

01:08:20.439 --> 01:08:24.630
So what we find is-- we
have to trace back the sign,

01:08:24.630 --> 01:08:34.100
but you find that the triplet
state symmetric in spin.

01:08:34.100 --> 01:08:38.720
And antisymmetric in the
spatial wave function.

01:08:38.720 --> 01:08:47.710
Has the lower energy,
is more strongly bound

01:08:47.710 --> 01:09:06.244
because the antisymmetric
spatial wave function reduces

01:09:06.244 --> 01:09:08.410
the repulsive interaction
between the two electrons.

01:09:15.660 --> 01:09:17.870
So in other words,
we do not have

01:09:17.870 --> 01:09:21.300
any spin term in
the Hamiltonian.

01:09:21.300 --> 01:09:24.700
It's just that whether
the spin wave function is

01:09:24.700 --> 01:09:28.990
symmetric or antisymmetric,
it requires the spatial wave

01:09:28.990 --> 01:09:31.760
function to be the opposite.

01:09:31.760 --> 01:09:36.040
And now when we calculate
the Coulomb energy

01:09:36.040 --> 01:09:39.420
for the spatial or antisymmetric
spatial wave function,

01:09:39.420 --> 01:09:41.370
we find a big difference.

01:09:41.370 --> 01:09:44.950
And the big difference
is the exchange energy.

01:09:44.950 --> 01:09:51.529
So it is a spin dependent
term for the total energy.

01:09:51.529 --> 01:09:56.810
But what is behind this energy
is simply the Coulomb energy.

01:09:56.810 --> 01:10:01.270
So the spin through the
symmetry of the wave function

01:10:01.270 --> 01:10:05.626
leads to a difference
in the Coulomb energy.

01:10:05.626 --> 01:10:07.000
And actually what
I'm telling you

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:12.140
is the explanation why we have
magnetism at room temperature.

01:10:12.140 --> 01:10:14.530
It was Heisenberg's
idea when he realized

01:10:14.530 --> 01:10:18.050
for the first time what
can cause ferromagnetism.

01:10:18.050 --> 01:10:23.160
It was pretty much the model
of the helium atom expanded

01:10:23.160 --> 01:10:26.620
to many, many
electrons in a lattice.

01:10:26.620 --> 01:10:30.260
So the result is that the
Curie temperature of thousands

01:10:30.260 --> 01:10:33.790
of degrees, we have magnetism
below 1,000 degrees.

01:10:33.790 --> 01:10:37.780
This energy scale is
an electronic energy,

01:10:37.780 --> 01:10:41.050
is in Coulomb energy scale
and not an energy scale

01:10:41.050 --> 01:10:43.190
where spin interactions
comes into play.

01:10:43.190 --> 01:10:45.530
If it were not for
the exchange energy,

01:10:45.530 --> 01:10:50.190
we would not have magnetic
materials above 1 calorie.

01:10:50.190 --> 01:10:52.310
So this is what you see
here in the helium atom.

01:10:52.310 --> 01:10:57.650
How speed leads to an
energy splitting which

01:10:57.650 --> 01:11:01.160
is an electronic Coulombic
energy splitting.

